{"parse":{"title":"Three Friends of Winter","pageid":32698969,"revid":859099245,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n</td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size: 125%; background-color: #b0c4de;\">\n<b>Three Friends of Winter</b></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Three Friends of Winter by Zhao Mengjian.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg/300px-Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"182\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg/450px-Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg/600px-Three_Friends_of_Winter_by_Zhao_Mengjian.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1000\" data-file-height=\"605\" /></a><div>The <i>Three Friends of Winter</i> by the painter Zhao Mengjian, <a href=\"/wiki/Song_dynasty\" title=\"Song dynasty\">Song dynasty</a></div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_characters\" title=\"Traditional Chinese characters\">Traditional&#160;Chinese</a></th><td>\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><span lang=\"zh-Hant\" title=\"Chinese language text\"><a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%AD%B2%E5%AF%92%E4%B8%89%E5%8F%8B\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wiktionary:\u6b72\u5bd2\u4e09\u53cb\">\u6b72\u5bd2\u4e09\u53cb</a></span></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Simplified_Chinese_characters\" title=\"Simplified Chinese characters\">Simplified Chinese</a></th><td>\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><span lang=\"zh-Hans\" title=\"Chinese language text\"><a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%B2%81%E5%AF%92%E4%B8%89%E5%8F%8B\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wiktionary:\u5c81\u5bd2\u4e09\u53cb\">\u5c81\u5bd2\u4e09\u53cb</a></span></span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<table class=\"collapsible collapsed\" style=\"padding:0;border:none;margin:-3px;width:auto;min-width:100%;font-size:100%;clear:none;float:none;background-color:transparent\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 100%; text-align: left; background-color: #f9ffbc;\">Transcriptions</th></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #dcffc9;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Standard_Chinese\" title=\"Standard Chinese\">Standard Mandarin</a></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Hanyu_Pinyin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hanyu Pinyin\">Hanyu Pinyin</a></th><td>\nsu\u00ech\u00e1n s\u0101ny\u01d2u</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr style=\"display:none\"><td colspan=\"2\">\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <b>Three Friends of Winter</b>, also known as <i><b>Suihan Sanyou</b></i>, is an art motif that comprises the <a href=\"/wiki/Pine\" title=\"Pine\">pine</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bamboo\" title=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Plum_blossom\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Plum blossom\">plum</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-brit_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-brit-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The Chinese observed that the pine, bamboo and plum do not wither as the cold days deepen into the winter season unlike many other plants.<sup id=\"cite_ref-npm-intro_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-npm-intro-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Known by them as the <i>Three Friends of Winter</i>, they entered the conventions of East Asian culture.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Together they symbolize steadfastness, perseverance, and resilience.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> They are highly regarded in <a href=\"/wiki/Confucianism\" title=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</a> and as such represent the scholar-gentleman's ideal.<sup id=\"cite_ref-brit_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-brit-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-welch-three_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-welch-three-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Cultural_symbolism\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Cultural symbolism</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three_Friends_of_Winter&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Three Friends of Winter are common in works of Chinese art<sup id=\"cite_ref-welch20_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-welch20-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and those cultures influenced by it. The three are first recorded as appearing together in a ninth-century poem by the poet Zhu Qingyu (\u6731\u6176\u9918) of the <a href=\"/wiki/Tang_dynasty\" title=\"Tang dynasty\">Tang dynasty</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-welch-three_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-welch-three-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The <a href=\"/wiki/Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty\" title=\"Culture of the Song dynasty\">Southern Song dynasty</a> artist Zhao Mengjian (\u8d99\u5b5f\u5805, c. 1199\u20131264), among others of the time, made this grouping popular in painting.<sup id=\"cite_ref-welch-three_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-welch-three-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The actual term \"Three Friends of Winter\" can be traced back to the earliest known mention in literature, the <i>Record of the Five-cloud Plum Cottage</i> (\u4e94\u96f2\u6885\u820d\u8a18) from <i>The Clear Mountain Collection</i> (\u973d\u5c71\u96c6) by the Song dynasty writer Lin Jingxi (\u6797\u666f\u7199, 1242\u20131310):<sup id=\"cite_ref-npm-intro_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-npm-intro-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-zh-npm-intro_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-zh-npm-intro-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<dl><dd><i>\"For his residence, earth was piled to form a hill and a hundred plum trees, which along with lofty pines and tall bamboo comprise the friends of winter, were planted.\"</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-npm-intro_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-npm-intro-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></dd>\n<dd>\u5373\u5176\u5c45\u7d2f\u571f\u70ba\u5c71\uff0c\u7a2e\u6885\u767e\u672c\uff0c\u8207\u55ac\u677e\uff0c\u8129\u7bc1\u70ba\u6b72\u5bd2\u53cb\u3002<sup id=\"cite_ref-zh-npm-intro_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-zh-npm-intro-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cultural_symbolism\">Cultural symbolism</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three_Friends_of_Winter&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Cultural symbolism\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bian_Wenjin,_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg/220px-Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"402\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg/330px-Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg/440px-Bian_Wenjin%2C_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"972\" data-file-height=\"1777\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bian_Wenjin,_Three_Friends_and_a_Hundred_Birds.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Three Friends and a Hundred Birds</i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Bian_Jingzhao\" title=\"Bian Jingzhao\">Bian Wenjin</a>, Ming dynasty</div></div></div>\n<p>Culturally, the <i>Three Friends of Winter</i>\u2014<a href=\"/wiki/Pine\" title=\"Pine\">pine</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bamboo#In_Asian_culture\" title=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Prunus_mume#Cultural_significance\" title=\"Prunus mume\">plum</a>\u2014are grouped together in the context of winter because they all flourish at that season.<sup id=\"cite_ref-brit_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-brit-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> For this reason they are commonly known as the <i>Three Friends of Winter</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-brit_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-brit-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  They are also referred to simply by their linked names: <i>Song Zhu Mei</i>  (\u677e\u7af9\u6885) in Chinese, transliterated as <i>Sho Chiku Bai</i> in Japanese (literally \"pine, bamboo, plum\").<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In a Korean poem by Kim Yuki (1580\u20131658), the three friends are brought together in order to underline the paradoxical contrast:\n</p>\n<dl><dd>Peach and plum of springtime, don't flaunt your pretty blossoms;</dd>\n<dd>Consider rather the old pine and green bamboo at year's end.</dd>\n<dd>What can change these noble stems and their flourishing evergreen?<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n<p>In Japan, they are particularly associated with the start of the Lunar New Year, appearing on greeting cards and as a design stamped into seasonal sweets.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three_Friends_of_Winter&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Four_Gentlemen\" title=\"Four Gentlemen\">Four Gentlemen of the Year</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Four_Treasures_of_the_Study\" title=\"Four Treasures of the Study\">Four Treasures of the Study</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three_Friends_of_Winter&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-brit-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-brit_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-brit_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-brit_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-brit_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/Chinese_symbols_1109.pdf\">\"Chinese symbols\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. British Museum. p.&#160;1<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">11 August</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Chinese+symbols&amp;rft.pages=1&amp;rft.pub=British+Museum&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britishmuseum.org%2Fpdf%2FChinese_symbols_1109.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree+Friends+of+Winter\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-npm-intro-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-npm-intro_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-npm-intro_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-npm-intro_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.npm.gov.tw/exh91/3friends/english/infor.htm\">\"The Three Friends of Winter: Paintings of Pine, Plum, and Bamboo from the Museum Collection (Introduction)\"</a>. National Palace Museum<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">10 August</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Three+Friends+of+Winter%3A+Paintings+of+Pine%2C+Plum%2C+and+Bamboo+from+the+Museum+Collection+%28Introduction%29&amp;rft.pub=National+Palace+Museum&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.npm.gov.tw%2Fexh91%2F3friends%2Fenglish%2Finfor.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree+Friends+of+Winter\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.colby.edu/art/InkTales/Bowdoin%20Exhibition%20Pages/BEThreeFriendsWinter.html\">\"Three Friends of Winter\"</a>. Colby College<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">10 August</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Three+Friends+of+Winter&amp;rft.pub=Colby+College&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.colby.edu%2Fart%2FInkTales%2FBowdoin%2520Exhibition%2520Pages%2FBEThreeFriendsWinter.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree+Friends+of+Winter\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.harvardartmuseums.org/exhibitions/past/detail.dot?id=19111\">\"Cultivating Virtue: Botanical Motifs and Symbols in East Asian Art\"</a>. Harvard Art Museums<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">11 August</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Cultivating+Virtue%3A+Botanical+Motifs+and+Symbols+in+East+Asian+Art&amp;rft.pub=Harvard+Art+Museums&amp;rft_